(44, 13, 31, 41, 16, 12, 14, 'his witnesses unto the people', 'Witnesses of the Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of witnesses who saw Jesus after his resurrection. Acts 13:31 mentions those who were witnesses, while Mark 16:14 highlights the disbelief of the eleven regarding those witnesses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 31, 42, 24, 36, 42, 'witnesses unto the people', 'Witnesses of the Resurrected Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing the resurrected Jesus. In Acts, the witnesses from Galilee to Jerusalem affirm the reality of Jesus'' resurrection, while in Luke, the disciples encounter the risen Jesus directly, reinforcing their role as witnesses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 45, 4, 13, 13, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises to Abraham', 'This connection highlights the theme of promises made to Abraham and his descendants. Both passages emphasize the significance of faith in relation to these promises.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 44, 26, 6, 6, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises to Fathers', 'Both passages emphasize the ''promise made unto the fathers,'' linking the hope of the promise to the message of salvation. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s promises throughout biblical history.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 26, 34, 23, 23, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Promise of Shepherd Leadership', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts, which relates to God''s commitment to provide a shepherd, as seen in Ezekiel. Both passages emphasize the theme of divine guidance through a leader, specifically referencing David as a shepherd figure.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 24, 23, 5, 5, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises and Kingship', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts 13:32, which is fulfilled in the righteous Branch mentioned in Jeremiah 23:5. Both passages emphasize the theme of a divinely appointed leader who will bring justice and prosperity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 33, 5, 2, 2, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises and Rulership', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts 13:32, which is fulfilled through the ruler mentioned in Micah 5:2. Both passages emphasize the significance of a leader arising from Bethlehem, linking the Old Testament prophecy to the New Testament declaration.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 38, 6, 12, 12, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Promise of the Branch', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts, which relates to the prophetic declaration of ''the man whose name is The BRANCH'' in Zechariah. Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of God''s promises through a significant figure who will build the temple.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 44, 13, 38, 38, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Promise and Forgiveness Connection', 'This connection highlights the continuity between the promise made to the fathers and the forgiveness of sins offered through Jesus. Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of God''s promise in the message of salvation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 33, 19, 2, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Sonship and Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine sonship as both passages declare, ''Thou art my Son; this day have I begotten thee.'' Acts 13:33 explicitly references Psalms 2:7, linking the resurrection of Jesus to the affirmation of His identity as God''s Son.', 'quotation', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 33, 58, 5, 5, 5, 'Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee', 'Connection of Sonship in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the declaration of Jesus as God''s Son. The phrase ''Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee'' appears in both contexts, linking Jesus'' identity and role.', 'quotation', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 33, 58, 1, 5, 6, 'Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee', 'Connection of Sonship in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' divine sonship. Both passages reference the phrase, ''Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee,'' emphasizing Jesus'' unique relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 23, 55, 3, 3, 'the sure mercies of David', 'Connection of Sure Mercies', 'Both passages emphasize the ''sure mercies of David,'' linking God''s promises to His covenant with David. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s faithfulness from the Old Testament to the New Testament.', 'keyword', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 19, 89, 2, 4, 'sure mercies of David', 'Mercies of David Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s covenant with David, as seen in both passages. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' which aligns with Psalms 89:2-4''s emphasis on God''s faithfulness and establishment of David''s throne.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 45, 6, 9, 9, 'raised him up from the dead', 'Resurrection and Eternal Life', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Christ and its implications for death. Acts 13:34 states that Christ was raised from the dead and will not return to corruption, while Romans 6:9 affirms that death has no more dominion over Him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 10, 7, 14, 16, 'sure mercies of David', 'Connection of God''s Promises', 'Both passages emphasize God''s enduring mercy and the establishment of a kingdom. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' which relates to the promise of an everlasting throne in 2 Samuel 7:14-16.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 19, 89, 19, 37, 'sure mercies of David', 'Connection of David''s Promises', 'Both passages emphasize God''s covenant with David and the assurance of his enduring lineage. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' which aligns with Psalms 89''s promise of David''s throne lasting forever.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 24, 33, 15, 17, 'the sure mercies of David', 'Connection of Righteousness and David', 'This connection highlights the promise of a righteous leader from David''s lineage, as seen in both passages. Acts 13:34 refers to the ''sure mercies of David,'' while Jeremiah 33:15-17 speaks of the ''Branch of righteousness'' that will arise from David.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 24, 33, 26, 26, 'sure mercies of David', 'Connection of Mercy and David', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mercy associated with David. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' while Jeremiah 33:26 speaks of having mercy on the seed of Jacob and David.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 19, 16, 10, 10, 'thine Holy One to see corruption', 'Connection of Holy One and Corruption', 'Both passages emphasize that God''s Holy One will not experience corruption. This connection highlights the assurance of preservation from death and decay.', 'quotation', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 44, 2, 27, 31, 'thine Holy One to see corruption', 'Connection of Resurrection Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize that God''s Holy One will not see corruption, highlighting the prophetic nature of David''s words regarding the resurrection of Christ. This connection illustrates the fulfillment of prophecy as seen in the New Testament.', 'prophecy', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 19, 49, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Corruption and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of not seeing corruption, suggesting a theme of eternal life or preservation from decay. This connection highlights the significance of the Holy One''s enduring existence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 42, 2, 26, 26, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not seeing death or corruption. Acts 13:35 speaks of the Holy One not seeing corruption, while Luke 2:26 reveals a promise of not seeing death before witnessing the Lord''s Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 43, 3, 36, 36, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption', 'Connection of Life and Corruption', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the Holy One not seeing corruption and the promise of everlasting life for believers. Both passages emphasize the significance of faith in relation to life and death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 43, 8, 51, 51, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of preservation from death. Acts 13:35 speaks of not seeing corruption, while John 8:51 emphasizes never seeing death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 44, 13, 36, 37, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.', 'Resurrection and Corruption', 'This connection highlights the contrast between David, who ''saw corruption,'' and Jesus, ''whom God raised again, saw no corruption.'' Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection and the preservation of the Holy One from decay.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 44, 2, 29, 29, 'David, after he had served his own generation', 'David''s Death and Burial', 'Both passages emphasize David''s death and burial, highlighting his mortality. Acts 13:36 mentions David falling asleep, while Acts 2:29 states he is dead and buried.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 10, 7, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection Between David''s Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of David''s death and legacy. Both passages mention David ''sleeping with his fathers,'' indicating a transition to the next generation and the continuation of his lineage.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 11, 2, 10, 10, 'fell on sleep', 'David''s Death and Burial', 'Both passages emphasize David''s death and burial. The phrase ''slept with his fathers'' in 1 Kings parallels the idea of David ''fell on sleep'' in Acts, highlighting the finality of his life.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 44, 13, 22, 22, NULL, 'David''s Fulfillment of God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize David''s role in fulfilling God''s will. Acts 13:22 highlights God''s testimony about David, while Acts 13:36 notes David''s service to his generation by God''s will.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
